row.entry:
NFS-GQD/N719:
λ ex = 370 nm
λ em = ~440 nm;

ce:section.ce:para:
Few researchers have used GQDs as co-sensitizers as an efficient approach for charge (electron and hole) transfer. Here, the dye is co-absorbed with GQD to increase the amount of charge injected into TiO2. The primary condition for this approach to work efficiently is by following the type-Ⅱ alignment (Fig. 6
                           ). The HOMO of dye lies above the HOMO of GQD. Dyes play a dual role: (i) efficient light absorber over the visible spectrum, and (ii) hole scavenger agents that induce separation of electron-hole pairs in GQD [126]. Dyes (acceptors) accept the positively charged holes from HOMO of GQD (donor), thus reducing the internal recombination in GQD. Hence, a more significant number of electrons are injected into TiO2 without recombining back with the hole in the HOMO of GQD. This type-Ⅱ alignment can be confirmed through 2 prerequisite conditions: (i) a significant overlap should occur between PL spectrum of the donor (GQD) and UV–vis spectrum of the acceptor (dye) at λ
                           ex, and (ii) gap of the donor (GQD) > acceptor (dye).
